all the way back to Europa,


498
0:36:50,166 --> 0:36:57,967
or whether my ancestors arrived much later.


499
0:36:57,967 --> 0:37:1,527
So I've got the results back of my DNA analysis


500
0:37:1,527 --> 0:37:3,527
and they look extraordinarily complicated,


501
0:37:3,527 --> 0:37:8,447
even though this is actually only a tiny fragment of my genetic code.


502
0:37:8,447 --> 0:37:13,847
And I've also got the genetic code for Europe's first lady, Europa,


503
0:37:13,847 --> 0:37:20,206
here in front of me, so I can compare our DNA sequences.


504
0:37:20,206 --> 0:37:31,126
At first sight we seem identical.


505
0:37:31,126 --> 0:37:33,487
But when you look really carefully,


506
0:37:33,487 --> 0:37:35,806
there are some differences.


507
0:37:35,806 --> 0:37:42,527
they may be tiny, but they're crucial.


508
0:37:42,527 --> 0:37:45,806
So this means I'm not descended from Europa.


509
0:37:45,806 --> 0:37:51,86
And in fact these mutations tell me that I'm descended


510
0:37:51,86 --> 0:37:59,86
from another European founding mother.


511
0:37:59,86 --> 0:38:1,847
Some have called this woman Iris,


512
0:38:1,847 --> 0:38:6,927
and her descendants may have been part of a new wave into Europe


513
0:38:6,927 --> 0:38:12,606
around 25,000 years ago.


514
0:38:12,606 --> 0:38:15,606
People that seem to have come from the east,


515
0:38:15,606 --> 0:38:25,646
bringing a new culture with them.


516
0:38:25,646 --> 0:38:29,166
I've come to the Czech Republic,


517
0:38:29,166 --> 0:38:32,927
to the small village of Doln/' Vestonice,


518
0:38:32,927 --> 0:38:38,887
famous for some big archaeological discoveries.


519
0:38:38,887 --> 0:38:50,166
So what do they reveal about this new culture?


520
0:38:50,166 --> 0:38:51,527
ROBERTS: Oh, that's beautiful.


521
0:38:51,527 --> 0:38:56,527
So, we've got several tusks like this in Central and Eastern Europe


522
0:38:56,527 --> 0:39:0,527
which always have a very complex type of engraving.


523
0:39:0,527 --> 0:39:3,927
And one thing that could be suggested


524
0:39:3,927 --> 0:39:7,246
is that this thing could be a meandering river.


525
0:39:7,246 --> 0:39:8,367
ROBERTS: Right.


526
0:39:8,367 --> 0:39:14,7
The way how the tusk is decorated could have had some sort of a meaning,


527
0:39:14,7 --> 0:39:18,806
like accessibility of the field or good for hunting, bad for hunting,


528
0:39:18,806 --> 0:39:22,286
you can push mammoth through or you cannot.


529
0:39:22,286 --> 0:39:24,367
-ROBERTS: So it's a map? -A kind of a map.


530
0:39:24,367 --> 0:39:28,206
And the whole strategy of an action could be planned


531
0:39:28,206 --> 0:39:36,86
on a piece of ivory like that.


532
0:39:36,86 --> 0:39:40,567
ROBERTS: We'll never know for sure if it was a map.


533
0:39:40,567 --> 0:39:49,126
But other artefacts found here are much more significant.


534
0:39:49,126 --> 0:39:53,967
this is the Venus of Doln/' Vestonice.


535
0:39:53,967 --> 0:40:6,47
One of the earliest pieces of pottery in the world.


536
0:40:6,47 --> 0:40:10,967
But the really exciting thing is that other Venus figurines


537
0:40:10,967 --> 0:40:18,726
have been unearthed all over the continent.


538
0:40:18,726 --> 0:40:22,47
What this means is that for the first time


539
0:40:22,47 --> 0:40:29,606
people shared a distinct culture right across Europe.


540
0:40:29,606 --> 0:40:32,86
But in the next few thousand years


541
0:40:32,86 --> 0:40:35,327
our European ancestors would face a threat


542
0:40:35,327 --> 0:40:39,86
that would almost wipe them out.


543
0:40:39,86 --> 0:40:43,327
(THuNDERCLAP)


544
0:40:43,327 --> 0:40:48,246
ROBERTS: Europe was about to experience devastating climate change.


545
0:40:48,246 --> 0:40:53,527
the peak of the Ice Age.


546
0:40:53,527 --> 0:40:59,606
Animals disappeared from the landscape and the ground froze over.


547
0:40:59,606 --> 0:41:9,927
Our ancestors couldn't survive in these Arctic conditions.


548
0:41:9,927 --> 0:41:15,286
By 24,000 years ago, Britain was uninhabitable,


549
0:41:15,286 --> 0:41:18,407
covered in ice half a mile thick.


550
0:41:18,407 --> 0:41:23,487
(WIND BLOWING)


551
0:41:23,487 --> 0:41:28,407
And still the ice sheets pushed further south,


552
0:41:28,407 --> 0:41:33,126
squeezing life from the land and almost wiping out


553
0:41:33,126 --> 0:41:39,686
our ancestors in Europe.


554
0:41:39,686 --> 0:41:43,7
This is the vezere valley in the Dordogne.


555
0:41:43,7 --> 0:41:45,847
During the last Ice Age, the hills around here


556
0:41:45,847 --> 0:41:48,527
would have been bound tight by frost.


557
0:41:48,527 --> 0:41:51,407
And with wind chill, the temperature up there


558
0:41:51,407 --> 0:41:55,726
could be as much as 20 degrees colder than down here in the valley,


559
0:41:55,726 --> 0:42:0,7
where a warmish micro-climate meant life could go on,


560
0:42:0,7 --> 0:42:3,766
and small bands of hunter-gatherers would've huddled together


561
0:42:3,766 --> 0:42:12,927
to survive the long, bitter winters.


562
0:42:12,927 --> 0:42:20,967
But they may not have survived at all, had it not been for this...


563
0:42:20,967 --> 0:42:28,246
the rock shelters and caves that riddle the landscape.


564
0:42:28,246 --> 0:42:35,927
And deep underground, they left something that we still marvel at today.


565
0:42:35,927 --> 0:43:7,686
(WATER DRIPPING)


566
0:43:7,686 --> 0:43:12,246
I'm in a cave called pech Merle, which is stunningly beautiful naturally,


567
0:43:12,246 --> 0:43:16,806
but look at this - this is real artistic expression.


568
0:43:16,806 --> 0:43:21,327
Something that defines us and sets us apart as a species.


569
0:43:21,327 --> 0:43:23,166
And pech Merle is unusual,


570
0:43:23,166 --> 0:43:26,567
because artists were coming here to paint these images


571
0:43:26,567 --> 0:43:30,806
both before and after the peak of the last Ice Age,


572
0:43:30,806 --> 0:43:33,806
generations of them returning to the cave


573
0:43:33,806 --> 0:43:39,726
as the world outside froze over.


574
0:43:39,726 --> 0:43:45,327
This is a very beautiful image and it uses the contours of the rock.


575
0:43:45,327 --> 0:43:49,567
The horse's back sort of curves along a bulge in the rock


576
0:43:49,567 --> 0:43:53,527
and there's an echo of the horse's head on this right side there.


577
0:43:53,527 --> 0:43:56,606
And it's obviously a very stylised horse as well.


578
0:43:56,606 --> 0:43:59,806
And I love the way those spots carry on into the background,


579
0:43:59,806 --> 0:44:4,367
as though the horse is sort of camouflaged against the rock.


580
0:44:4,367 --> 0:44:8,327
And there's a hand placed against the rock just above the horse's back.


581
0:44:8,327 --> 0:44:11,887
I mean, that is amazing, isn't it? That's an Ice Age hand.


582
0:44:11,887 --> 0:44:17,726
(SpUTTERING)


583
0:44:17,726 --> 0:44:23,286
Michel Lorblanchet has devoted his life to studying the art found in caves


584
0:44:23,286 --> 0:44:24,686
like Pech Merle.


585
0:44:24,686 --> 0:44:35,246
(SpUTTERING)


586
0:44:35,246 --> 0:44:39,246
I think I naively imagined that you just take a mouthful of charcoal,


587
0:44:39,246 --> 0:44:42,567
a bit of water and just spit it at the wall and that'd be it.


588
0:44:42,567 --> 0:44:44,967
But of course all that would happen would be that the mess


589
0:44:44,967 --> 0:44:48,927
would run down the wall and obscure the stencil that you were trying to do.


590
0:44:48,927 --> 0:44:52,126
So you have to do it like this, using an almost dry mouth,


591
0:44:52,126 --> 0:45:3,726
and just building it up very gradually with a fine spray.


592
0:45:3,726 --> 0:45:7,246
Michel Lorblanchet did a recreation of the horses at pech Merle


593
0:45:7,246 --> 0:45:10,447
using this technique. It took him a whole week.


594
0:45:10,447 --> 0:45:12,86
-Is it finished? -Yes...


595
0:45:12,86 --> 0:45:15,367
-It's finished. -Yes. That's right.


596
0:45:15,367 --> 0:45:21,447
ROBERTS: But what drove these people, struggling just to survive, to paint?


597
0:45:21,447 --> 0:45:25,246
The vast majority of these images seem to be animals,


598
0:45:25,246 --> 0:45:28,487
there don't seem to be many representations of humans.


599
0:45:28,487 --> 0:45:32,686
No, that's true, they are mainly animal figures.


600
0:45:32,686 --> 0:45:38,367
And for them, of course, animals were not only game,


601
0:45:38,367 --> 0:45:41,86
but also spirits, symbolic,


602
0:45:41,86 --> 0:45:45,447
so the animal figures are, in fact, symbolic figures.


603
0:45:45,447 --> 0:45:49,47
And going into pech Merle, I mean, it's such a beautiful cave


604
0:45:49,47 --> 0:45:51,246
with all the stalactites hanging down


605
0:45:51,246 --> 0:45:56,246
and it does feel as though it was, I don't know, almost a temple.


606
0:45:56,246 --> 0:45:59,47
Yes, that's right, this is a natural temple, if you like.


607
0:45:59,47 --> 0:46:1,606
They are sacred sites.


608
0:46:1,606 --> 0:46:4,766
They are not painting just for fun.


609
0:46:4,766 --> 0:46:8,927
By painting a cave and having a sanctuary,


610
0:46:8,927 --> 0:46:15,286
it is a way for them to say, ''Here is our sacred place.''


611
0:46:15,286 --> 0:46:22,646
The painted cave is symbolic of the whole tribe.


612
0:46:22,646 --> 0:46:25,447
ROBERTS: Being bound together in this way


613
0:46:25,447 --> 0:46:28,7
may have helped our ancestors survive


614
0:46:28,7 --> 0:46:36,487
the kind of climate change that only haunts our imaginations today.


615
0:46:36,487 --> 0:46:40,286
(WIND BLOWING)


616
0:46:40,286 --> 0:46:45,327
Nearly two thirds of modern Europeans can trace their lineages back


617
0:46:45,327 --> 0:46:55,606
to ancestors who held on in those southern refuges.


618
0:46:55,606 --> 0:46:58,686
It would be more than 1 00 generations


619
0:46:58,686 --> 0:47:7,86
before the world would begin to warm again.


620
0:47:7,86 --> 0:47:11,327
And it may have been around this time that something happened


621
0:47:11,327 --> 0:47:15,967
which would stamp a new identity on the Europeans.


622
0:47:15,967 --> 0:47:18,766
Since the birth of our species in Africa,


623
0:47:18,766 --> 0:47:22,847
our ancestors' skin had almost certainly been dark,


624
0:47:22,847 --> 0:47:26,606
protection against the tropical sun.


625
0:47:26,606 --> 0:47:34,606
But why in Europe did it turn from brown to white?


626
0:47:34,606 --> 0:47:39,967
the surprising answer may lie with a single vitamin.


627
0:47:39,967 --> 0:47:42,407
Vitamin D.


628
0:47:42,407 --> 0:47:45,646
A lack of vitamin D may not sound particularly significant,


629
0:47:45,646 --> 0:47:48,367
but it can be life-threatening.


630
0:47:48,367 --> 0:47:50,646
It can wreak havoc with a growing skeleton,


631
0:47:50,646 --> 0:47:54,166
causing bones to grow bent and misshapen.


632
0:47:54,166 --> 0:47:57,766
These are all skeletons of patients with rickets,


633
0:47:57,766 --> 0:48:0,286
and you can see how it's affected the bones.


634
0:48:0,286 --> 0:48:5,286
These leg bones here are all curved, making walking difficult.


635
0:48:5,286 --> 0:48:9,887
And the chest is deformed, so breathing would be problematic as well.


636
0:48:9,887 --> 0:48:14,327
And not only that, rickets can affect your chance of having children.


637
0:48:14,327 --> 0:48:17,967
This is the pelvis of a woman who had rickets.


638
0:48:17,967 --> 0:48:21,726
And you can see the way that the pelvic bones have collapsed together.


639
0:48:21,726 --> 0:48:25,606
You just could not get a baby's head through this space.


640
0:48:25,606 --> 0:48:32,686
It would've been impossible for her to give birth naturally.


641
0:48:32,686 --> 0:48:35,367
So vitamin D is vital


642
0:48:35,367 --> 0:48:40,166
and we make it in our skin in the presence of sunlight.


643
0:48:40,166 --> 0:48:42,927
But dark skin blocks out the sun,


644
0:48:42,927 --> 0:48:47,847
and in Europe, with its weaker sunlight, this could've been a problem.


645
0:48:47,847 --> 0:48:52,686
Our ancestors may have struggled to make enough vitamin D.


646
0:48:52,686 --> 0:49:5,527
So this could be why Europeans turned white.


647
0:49:5,527 --> 0:49:8,527
But this change in skin colour was nothing


648
0:49:8,527 --> 0:49:18,686
compared with the massive upheaval approaching.


649
0:49:18,686 --> 0:49:20,927
I'm heading back to turkey,


650
0:49:20,927 --> 0:49:25,686
because a recent discovery here shows that after the Ice Age,


651
0:49:25,686 --> 0:49:29,527
our ancestors abandoned their way of life,


652
0:49:29,527 --> 0:49:38,847
one they had followed since our species first appeared in Africa.


653
0:49:38,847 --> 0:49:52,887
And what happened here still defines our world today.


654
0:49:52,887 --> 0:49:58,527
this final stage of my European journey leads to a remote hillside


655
0:49:58,527 --> 0:50:4,847
in the far south of the country.


656
0:50:4,847 --> 0:50:7,927
This is Gobekli Tepe,


657
0:50:7,927 --> 0:50:16,686
an extraordinary site that I'm just incredibly excited to look at.


658
0:50:16,686 --> 0:50:18,86
Hi. Alice.


659
0:50:18,86 --> 0:50:19,606
-Are you Klaus Schmidt? -Nice to meet you.


660
0:50:19,606 --> 0:50:20,967
Hello. I'm Alice Roberts.


661
0:50:20,967 --> 0:50:22,967
(LAuGHS) I heard from your visit. Yeah.


662
0:50:22,967 --> 0:50:24,927
Nice to meet you here in Gobekli Tepe.


663
0:50:24,927 --> 0:50:26,686
I'm so excited about coming here.


664
0:50:26,686 --> 0:50:28,567
It's such an amazing discovery you've made.


665
0:50:28,567 --> 0:50:30,246
It's amazing, that's true, that's very true.


666
0:50:30,246 --> 0:50:32,47
-You seem very excited. -I just this season


667
0:50:32,47 --> 0:50:33,646
we have a lot of new findings.


668
0:50:33,646 --> 0:50:53,487
-So it's worth to have a look. -Oh, come on then, let's have a look.


669
0:50:53,487 --> 0:50:57,887
ROBERTS: Gobekli tepe is 12,000 years old,


670
0:50:57,887 --> 0:51:3,487
over twice as old as the pyramids.


671
0:51:3,487 --> 0:51:9,166
Already, Klaus has found dozens of standing stones,


672
0:51:9,166 --> 0:51:17,166
each one carved with mysterious symbols.


673
0:51:17,166 --> 0:51:22,766
these stone circles are possibly the oldest purpose-built temples


674
0:51:22,766 --> 0:51:31,806
in the world.


675
0:51:31,806 --> 0:51:36,246
KLAuS: Sometimes, there are arms and hands and fingers depicted.


676
0:51:36,246 --> 0:51:41,166
So it's very clear that the T part is a human head in profile


677
0:51:41,166 --> 0:51:45,286
and the shaft of the pillar is the human body.


678
0:51:45,286 --> 0:51:49,47
Here we have an example of the depiction of an arm


679
0:51:49,47 --> 0:51:51,567
which is going down here, and the fingers.


680
0:51:51,567 --> 0:51:54,47
The hand and the fingers are not excavated yet,


681
0:51:54,47 --> 0:51:58,487
but it's clear they will appear when we continue to work here.


682
0:51:58,487 --> 0:52:2,47
So we've got a circle of smaller T-shaped pillars


683
0:52:2,47 --> 0:52:4,246
and then two enormous ones in the centre.


684
0:52:4,246 --> 0:52:7,606
It's always the same, there are two in the centre which are very big


685
0:52:7,606 --> 0:52:11,726
and free-standing, surrounded by smaller but similar ones.


686
0:52:11,726 --> 0:52:13,527
And we understand it as a meeting,


687
0:52:13,527 --> 0:52:25,527
as a gathering of these beings made of stone.


688
0:52:25,527 --> 0:52:28,606
Here now, we have the most interesting reliefs.


689
0:52:28,606 --> 0:52:29,686
ROBERTS: Oh, wow.


690
0:52:29,686 --> 0:52:33,327
KLAuS: Ibis, snake and a vulture.


691
0:52:33,327 --> 0:52:36,47
It's a story illustrated by these animals,


692
0:52:36,47 --> 0:52:38,206
and this story is not a peaceful one.


693
0:52:38,206 --> 0:52:40,367
A scorpion, snake, and so on.


694
0:52:40,367 --> 0:52:43,686
Our model for the function of all this installation is


695
0:52:43,686 --> 0:52:46,567
they have been made for burial reasons.


696
0:52:46,567 --> 0:52:50,407
To bring the dead bodies to open places


697
0:52:50,407 --> 0:52:53,126
and the vultures are eating the flesh and other birds.


698
0:52:53,126 --> 0:52:56,166
So you think this might have been a site for these sky burials?


699
0:52:56,166 --> 0:52:58,166
-KLAuS: Yes, yes... -Where people are left out in the open


700
0:52:58,166 --> 0:53:0,86
to be picked clean by vultures.


701
0:53:0,86 --> 0:53:1,927
-KLAuS: Yes... -And these are the vultures?


702
0:53:1,927 --> 0:53:3,407
KLAuS: (LAuGHS) These are the vultures, yeah.


703
0:53:3,407 --> 0:53:5,407
ROBERTS: It almost looks like hieroglyphics.


704
0:53:5,407 --> 0:53:14,7
Maybe pre-hieroglyphic messages or Stone Age hieroglyphics.


705
0:53:14,7 --> 0:53:18,927
ROBERTS: Klaus is anxious to show me his most spectacular discovery.


706
0:53:18,927 --> 0:53:20,327
KLAuS: And here we found...


707
0:53:20,327 --> 0:53:21,447
(ROBERTS EXCLAIMS)


708
0:53:21,447 --> 0:53:23,166
...this nice animal.


709
0:53:23,166 --> 0:53:26,766
This is incredibly beautiful, I mean, this is sculpture.


710
0:53:26,766 --> 0:53:28,286
-It's not just a relief, is it? -Yeah, yeah, sure.


711
0:53:28,286 --> 0:53:29,726
ROBERTS: It's wonderful. KLAuS: Yes, clearly,


712
0:53:29,726 --> 0:53:32,447
it's a masterpiece of work.


713
0:53:32,447 --> 0:53:36,527
ROBERTS: It makes you rethink the Stone Age, doesn't it? I mean, it...


714
0:53:36,527 --> 0:53:39,407
You tend to think of hunter-gatherers as being, I don't know,


715
0:53:39,407 --> 0:53:41,927
fairly crude in some ways,


716
0:53:41,927 --> 0:53:46,806
and not necessarily capable of producing artefacts that beautiful.


717
0:53:46,806 --> 0:53:50,7
It's clear that these societies had specialists


718
0:53:50,7 --> 0:53:51,806
for stone-working, at least.


719
0:53:51,806 --> 0:53:55,686
So, really, people who didn't do anything else, as to produce sculptures


720
0:53:55,686 --> 0:53:57,646
and pillars and reliefs from stone.


721
0:53:57,646 --> 0:53:59,487
These are such exciting finds, aren't they?


722
0:53:59,487 --> 0:54:3,327
KLAuS: Yeah.


723
0:54:3,327 --> 0:54:8,367
ROBERTS: this place suggests a society that could support specialist craftsmen


724
0:54:8,367 --> 0:54:13,7
and perhaps even a priesthood.


725
0:54:13,7 --> 0:54:16,887
It was the beginning of a totally new way of life.


726
0:54:16,887 --> 0:54:18,927
KLAuS: These are sites of settled hunters.


727
0:54:18,927 --> 0:54:21,646
So it was a high culture of hunters here,


728
0:54:21,646 --> 0:54:25,407
which was nearly exploding in the tenth millennium,


729
0:54:25,407 --> 0:54:28,327
so it's still a hunter-gatherer society in its structures,


730
0:54:28,327 --> 0:54:30,927
and its buildings, its monuments.


731
0:54:30,927 --> 0:54:33,447
ROBERTS: But there was another very important difference


732
0:54:33,447 --> 0:54:37,887
between these hunter-gatherers and any of their predecessors.


733
0:54:37,887 --> 0:54:43,806
they were settling down, abandoning their nomadic lifestyle.


734
0:54:43,806 --> 0:54:50,606
A huge shift, which would help spark a Europe-wide revolution.


735
0:54:50,606 --> 0:54:59,407
And the evidence for this can be found growing in the surrounding fields.


736
0:54:59,407 --> 0:55:3,166
Locked inside this single stalk of wheat


737
0:55:3,166 --> 0:55:7,447
is a story of how the world was transformed.


738
0:55:7,447 --> 0:55:12,7
Geneticists have analysed DNA from domesticated wheat varieties


739
0:55:12,7 --> 0:55:15,766
from across the world, and the staggering thing is


740
0:55:15,766 --> 0:55:25,726
they can all be traced back to grasses which originally grew in this area.


